title: For Sale:  DANGER - Please be very careful
postcontent:
To anyone who believes it is a good idea to flag ads you think are priced too high (or conversely too low) and, even worse, try to enlist others to do the same.

You are embarking upon a very dangerous course of action believing you should be the arbiter of pricing.  That is the same type of behavior in which this administration engages.  If they don't like the way a market is working (e.g. the housing market) they then attempt to impose their views, values and beliefs upon the market and "move" pricing in the direction they think is "fair"...and we see how well that worked out.  If they don't like the views, values or beliefs of those with whom they differ, they attack them and attempt to silence them...witness the "gun ban/restriction" nightmare we are potentially facing.  Your attempt to force pricing down (or up) or force people out of the market by flagging them is absolutely no different and will have a very negative impact on this site.  Do you also advocate going on Gunbroker and forbidding people to offer their firearms up for auction because their opening bid or reserve is too high...or would you try and forbid someone to bid higher than the price you think the gun is worth?  

Similarly, will you also flag someone who is offering their firearm or ammo at an extremely low price?  I imagine you would simply buy it.

I would respectfully suggest and ask that you just allow the "free" market to work.  "Free" meaning sellers have the right to ask any price they choose and buyers have the right to bid any price they choose irrespective of what anyone else might think of those prices.  I personally can't believe some of the prices that are asked by sellers but, similarly, I also have to smile at some of the prices that are bid by buyers.  However, if I think the price is too high, I simply don't buy...I might even sell if prices get really stupid.  Does that make me a thief?  Similarly, if I see a really low price, I will buy.  Does that also make me a thief?  

The reality is that if prices are ridiculously high and no one buys then ultimately the seller, assuming they truly want to sell, will necessarily lower the price until such time as a buyer thinks it is a "fair" price and buys.

On the other hand, if someone does buy, at "whatever" price, I struggle to see why that would bother anyone.  If you want to buy .223 at $2.00 or $20.00 per round, what concern of mine is that?  Clearly your view of prices would be radically different than mine but you might think they are going to tax ammunition out of existence such that you could never buy it again.  Even though we might disagree as to what is a good or "fair" price or what that ammo is "worth", it would be your right to buy it at that price (and the seller's right to sell it at that price) and absolutely no business or concern of mine.  I would suggest that any price that is agreed to between a willing buyer and willing seller, no matter how high, low or objectionable any of us may find it, is by definition "fair" and "worth" it.

Firearm and ammo prices are high for a reason.  If ammo was readily available people couldn't ask and get the prices they are getting.  The problem is that it is not readily available.  Have you been to Walmart or your local gun shop and seen their shelves?  They are pretty barren.  Prices on firearms are high because demand is going through the roof.  Whether we like it or not, it is a reality.  There are external forces (primarily the Obama administration) that are driving demand, and thus the prices, up.  The greatest cause of this is the administration's desire to further constrain the supply of firearms and ammunition.  The supply of firearms is relatively constant but the demand is going through the roof.  Thus prices have to go up.

I have been both a buyer and a seller on this site for several years.  I want to see what is available in the market (both on the sell side and the buy side)...at any price.  I would seriously hate to see the market dry up or the volume of offerings decrease because some people feel they should be able to determine what a gun or ammo someone else wants to buy or sell is "worth".
